DevNetwork/ DeveloperWeek Conf.Hybrid (virtual + in-person finals)Feb 2026 (online phase + Feb 18– 19, 2026 finals at DevWeek Conf)Online + San Jose, CALargest open hackathon (~1000+ participants) co-located with DeveloperWeek (industry conference) . Open to students and professionals; dozens of tech companies sponsor challenge prizes (APIs, cloud, etc.). While prizes are typically cash or gadgets, sponsors often recruit from the pool of finalists. Being a top team can lead to networking with hiring managers from sponsor companies (many Silicon Valley firms attend).DevWeek 2026 Hackathon (register online; free with DevWeek pass) Tips & Recommendations: Apply Early & Prepare: Many student hackathons (e.g. HackMIT, TreeHacks) require an application. Meet deadlines and highlight any projects or skills on the application. Prepare by brushing up on coding challenges and familiarizing yourself with hackathon themes or sponsor technologies (for example, know some basics of the APIs/cloud services that sponsors like to see used).29 3029 31 • 10 Focus on Networking: Hackathons with company sponsors are prime recruiting grounds. Take advantage of networking lounges, sponsor workshops, and career fairs during the event. Introduce yourself to company reps, ask about internship programs, and show genuine interest in their tech . For virtual segments (like Code to Give’s online phase ), engage actively on Slack/Discord and during mentor sessions. Target Sponsor Prizes: Many hackathons offer sponsor-specific prizes (e.g. “Best Use of X API”). Pursuing a sponsor challenge can put you on that sponsor’s radar. Even if you don’t win, demonstrating interest in a company’s technology (say, building on JPMorgan’s challenge at Code for Good) can be a conversation starter with recruiters. Leverage Mentor Feedback: Events like Code for Good and Code to Give pair you with employee mentors . Treat this as an informal interview – ask mentors about their work culture and tech stack, and show your problem-solving approach. Often mentors provide input to recruiters on participant performance. Showcase Teamwork and Learning: Companies at these hackathons look for collaborative and quick learners. During judging or any follow-up interviews, emphasize what you learned and how you contributed in a team under time pressure. Hackathon projects don’t need to be perfect – passion and adaptability count. By strategically choosing hackathons known for recruitment and actively engaging with sponsors, an SJSU MSSE student can not only have fun building projects but also significantly boost their internship prospects.
